args: Thank you for helping me dry the laundry,\nElisanne.
Not at all; we all owe you our deepest\ngratitude for always washing it.\nIn fact, I... Hmm?
Can you hear someone singing over there?
Ah, Lucretia. Her voice is SO beautiful.
Yes, it's filled with warmth and kindness.
...Hmm? Oh, hello, you two.\nWere you listening to me?
I apologize for doing so without asking.\nYour voice was so beautiful that we\nsimply could not help ourselves.
You truly are a singular talent.
I'm glad to see that you haven't fallen out\nof love with singing, at least.
Elsewise you would not be able to\ncreate such joyous music.
No, you're right—I don't dislike singing.\nOn the contrary, I love it.
Singing is who I am; how could I possibly\nfall out of love with it?
Then why did you decide to give it up as\na career?
I imagine you pursued that career in the\nfirst place due to your love of music, yes?
I answer your question with another:\nYou put much hard work into becoming a\nPaladyn, did you not?
Hm? Well, yes, of course.\nBut that was my dream.
I knew it would be a thorny path,\nbut I did not let that deter me.
I spared no efforts in pursuing this dream.
In much the same way, I spared no effort\nwhen pursuing my singing career.
I practiced from morning to night,\nand sometimes on to the dawn.
Then how could you give up so easily on\nwhat you worked so hard to obtain?
Because I...I don't know what I am doing\nany more.
I don't understand what purpose there is\nin my taking the stage as a songstress.
Oh, that's what my fans are expecting\nfrom me, and no mistake.
They expect the perfection and beauty that\nmy songs have come to be associated\nwith. Nothing else will satisfy them.
So what would happen if I was to take\nthe stage and sing something different?
I imagine that some of them would be\nquite disappointed.
Very much so. And yet, I do not sing to\nsatisfy people's expectations—I do it\nbecause I love it.
But so long as I wish to keep singing,\nI must be the performer people expect.
The more time I spent thinking about this,\nthe more frustrated and unsure I became.
I think I understand what you're saying.
And yet, I also believe you are being \nmore than a little naive.

If you intend to make a living by singing,
then answering the expectations of an
audience is simply part of the job, is
it not?
Oh, I know that. Believe me.
And I always knew it would be difficult to\nkeep answering such expectations.
But more than anything, I wanted to sing.\nNow, however, I see that perhaps I wasn't\nas prepared for this as I thought.
I apologize if that was too forward.\nI know nothing about your chosen path,\nafter all.
I just fear that if this continues,\nI may lose the will to sing entirely.
All right, that's enough of serious talk\nfor one day.
Incidentally, are you a fan of sweets,\nLucretia?
I am, actually. Why do you ask?
Because nothing cheers a person feeling\nlow so much as sweets.
Though if they aren't available, eating any\nfood you enjoy can have a similar effect.
I understand that singing is an important\nsubject for you, which is why you are\ndwelling on it so.

Still, it's vital to rest from time to time.
Sometimes, the more desperate you are to
find an answer, the easier it slips through
your fingers.
Well, now that you mentioned sweets,\nI realize that I'm rather hungry.\nShall we stop for some food?
I've baked some real treats today.\nI'm sure you will like them.
Thank you. I'd love to try some.
Mmm! This chiffon cake is spectacular!
Heh. I knew you would like it. I put a lot of\neffort into making the cream just right.
The sweetness level is perfect.\nI think I could eat this all day.
Maybe I should try making some myself.
Ha ha! Don't worry—I was only joking.
You never struck me as the joking type.
Really? Even I have a sense of humor,\nyou know. Although it does feel like\nsome time since I've tried to use it.
I'd almost forgotten that I used to be able\nto smile like this.
I suppose I have the two of you to thank\nfor helping me to remember.
You're very welcome. Now, if you want\nmore cake, I have plenty left.
